children.subject: If ramchandran, he curves to a B+ because he knows that the classmates are so advanced. As an A student in CS70 I am like a mean student in 126 right now.
followup, how hard is it to get a good grade in 126?

history.content:
Currently taking 126 and took 170 last fall. I personally don't find it harder or more work than 170 but your mileage may vary depending on how good your intuition is. I'd assume it's harder to get a good grade in 126 than in 170 just cause the class is more self-selective and the people in that class probably already have a knack for that line of thinking



__



2nd person here, taking 126/170 rn, 126 is about 1.5-2x harder than 170 in terms of pure difficulty. Workload is the same, just harder. 


---


I found 126 way harder than 170 purely because the population of 126 is so much more advanced as it's very self-selecting.


--- 


Just wanted to throw another datapoint out there. I took them together a few semesters ago and personally found 126 to be much easier than 170 (still not easy by any means though). Maybe it's because I enjoyed the material a lot more; I also thought it was a lot more straight forward but that's just my opinion.

children.subject: It's pretty orthogonal ... it's mainly deeper 70/134 probability + applications in a variety of info theory/systems. if you like 170 because of probelm solving, this class is like problem solving on steroids.

How interesting/useful is the class?

I’ve loved 170. Will I get a similar experience with 126?

Probability on an EECS level means there’s lots of tricks in problem solving. Thus historically the class has been very difficult, and as a result only those who wish to rise to the challenge took it. However this changed recently as Prof Sahai touted the class as necessary to getting the most out of 189, prompting me and ofher students to take it.
Can anyone elaborate a bit on why exactly is this class, in particular, 'self-selecting'?
